<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-761-557  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 761 557.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 17 1989 v6 n28 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>States take steps to crack down on network hackers: legislationaimed at preventing net virus attacks.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>State governments are taking steps to enhance the security oftheir computer networks and crack down on computer crime.andO;California, Florida, New York and Pennsylvania have passed or areawaiting approval of legislation designed to outlaw virus attacksor to require state agencies to adopt security measures.andP;  New Yorkstate senator Roy Goodman has suggested the creation of a centralagency to oversee compliance with computer network securitystandards by state agencies.andP;  Florida is one of the first statesto take notice of the seriousness of computer break-ins.andP;  Itsagencies use a statewide backbone network for voice communicationsand are in the process of migrating their data traffic onto thebackbone.andP;  The state is also researching ways to protectcommercial networks from computer hackers.andP;  California is revisingthe definition of computer networks to put more substance into itsexisting computer crime laws.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesComputer HackersSecurityNetworksCaliforniaFloridaNew YorkPennsylvaniaGovernment AgencyLegislation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>